data.value: Acetylcholine is an important neurotransmitter in both the central and peripheral nervous systems. The most common effect of acetylcholine in the brain is arousal, achieved. Largely through muscarinic receptors. Acetylcholine is also the neurotransmitter of post-ganglion parasympathetic pathways that innervate the cord, glandular tissue and visceral smooth muscles, mediating effects through muscarinic receptors.

data.value: Amino acids are the most abundant neurotransmitters in the central nervous system and are represented by: Glutamate, aspartate, glycine, GABA (g-aminobutyric acid), taurine. From a functional point of view, amino acids can be divided into two categories: Excitators and inhibitors. • Excitatory amino acids. L-glutamate and L-aspartate are the neurotransmitters used by most excitatory neurones in the central nervous system. • Amino acids inhibitors. GABA, spread throughout the central nervous system, and glycine, especially found in the spinal cord and brain stem, are the mediators of inhibitory synapses in the central nervous system.

data.name: label9.Text
data.value: Research on the chemical transfer of information to synapses gradually expanded into the central nervous system, laying the foundations for brain neurochemistry, which was able to determine the molecular structure of neurotransmitter and neuromodulatory substances and established the biochemical stages of synaptic transmission. These steps are: • Synthesis in the pericarion of the neurotransmitter. • Transport and storage in the synaptic vesicles from the axonal endings. • Release of the neurotransmitter into the synaptic slit through exocytosis under the influence of the nervous impulse. • Coupling the neurotransmitter with receptors on the postsynaptic membrane. Inactivation of the neurotransmitter through enzymatic or reuptake processes. Neurotransmitter and neuromodulatory substances have been highlighted by a number of methods such as fluorescence microscopy, radioisotope marking autohiography, electronic m-spectroscopy, immunocytochemistry techniques based on the specificity of antibodies to enzymes that mediate synaptic transmission. Thanks to these methods, more than 60 neurotransmitter and neuromodulatory substances have been discovered so far, which have been classified into four large groups: Neuropeptides, biogenic monoamines, amino acids, non-peptidergic mediators.
